1.5, identify the function where there is a bug. You do not have to
identify the bug itself, only its location, but note that this must be
the location of the underlying error, which is not necessarily where
the error manifests itself or is "noticed" by the client.


      Executable         Function with the underlying error
===============================================================
         ./bdtBad1        BDT_insert (No init check)
---------------------------------------------------------------
         ./bdtBad2        BDT_rm (No shift after remove)
---------------------------------------------------------------
         ./bdtBad3        BDT_insert (Not inserting new nodes along path)
                              When inserting a node with a previously
                              non-existant parent node, the parent
                              node being isn't created.
---------------------------------------------------------------
         ./bdtBad4        BDT_strlenAccumulate (off by one at each stage leading to not
	 allocating enough memory for the string)
---------------------------------------------------------------
         ./bdtBad5        BDT_findNode (missing Path_free in one of the cases)
===============================================================

------------------------------------------------------------------------
What are your critiques of the given DT implementations, as
specified in Step 2.5?


1. Each Node knows its entire path which is extraneuous. 
Each node should only know exactly what it needs and no more. So,
it should only store its relative path. Further, storing the absolute path
leads to situations in which illegal states can be represented because
a parent and child directory have incompatible absolute paths. 

2. In Node_new, you specify the path and the parent. This is not ideal 
because the path and the parent may disagree. This is not minimal. It 
should be possible to determine the parent from the path. 

3. The parameter order is also sometimes inconsistent. For example,
Node_new and Node_hasChild take path and parent parameters in the 
opposite order. 

4. In terms of naming conventions, having the node sometimes called
oNParent is confusing when the function returns info about that node.
For example, the parameter in Node_getNumChildren should probably
just be oNNode



